`crates/ctx-scan` is the whole ctx-scan tool: a git-agnostic directory scanner that maintains a `.context/` summary tree via content hashing, exposed as both a CLI/Stop-hook binary and a library (`runner::scan_run/check_run/update_run`, `cli::stop_hook`). Depending on it gets you zero-cost staleness detection (`--check`) and targeted regeneration (`--update`, `stop_hook`) without any git requirement.

`src/` and `tests/` are two halves of one contract: `src` implements the walker → hash → runner pipeline and its two dispatch surfaces (CLI, Stop-hook); `tests` pins the exact freshness/regeneration semantics of that pipeline as black-box specs, including a hermetic in-memory harness (`FakeFs`/`RecordingAgent`) for `scan.rs` and a real-fs-only path for `stop_hook.rs`. Both sides agree on one invariant: `stop_hook` never mutates tree freshness or invokes the agent, while `scan_run`/non-fresh `update_run` are the only writers of hash sidecars — a change to `Staleness` field order, `hash::diff` ordering, or `check_run`'s fresh/stale semantics must be updated in `runner.rs` and both test files simultaneously.

The tests further depend on real prompt files under `../../prompts` relative to `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR`; renaming or moving those breaks both `scan.rs` and `stop_hook.rs`.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.